    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="faq-section inspector-faq-section" id="faq">
  <div class="container faq-container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <p class="section-subtitle inspector-compact-subtitle">Quick answers for event inspection, track/channel logic, timing checks, and quality flags.</p>

    <div class="accordion" id="inspector-faq-accordion">
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <div class="accordion-header" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false">
          <h3>What does this MIDI Inspector show?</h3>
          <span class="accordion-icon"><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></span>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-content">
          <p>It shows MIDI events, tracks, channels, notes, tempo changes, time signatures, and quality indicators such as overlap or dangling notes.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accordion-item">
        <div class="accordion-header" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false">
          <h3>Does this upload my MIDI files?</h3>
          <span class="accordion-icon"><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></span>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-content">
          <p>No. Inspection runs locally in your browser. Your MIDI files stay on your device.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accordion-item">
        <div class="accordion-header" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false">
          <h3>Why is track always 1?</h3>
          <span class="accordion-icon"><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></span>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-content">
          <p>Many MIDI files are single-track. In that case, channels and programs are often the best way to distinguish parts.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accordion-item">
        <div class="accordion-header" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false">
          <h3>What is the difference between track and channel?</h3>
          <span class="accordion-icon"><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></span>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-content">
          <p>A track is part of the file structure. A channel is a MIDI routing layer often used for instruments or parts. One track can contain many channels.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accordion-item">
        <div class="accordion-header" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false">
          <h3>How do I inspect tempo and time signature changes?</h3>
          <span class="accordion-icon"><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></span>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-content">
          <p>Open the Events view and look for tempo and timeSig rows.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accordion-item">
        <div class="accordion-header" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false">
          <h3>What do overlap, dangling, and orphanOff mean?</h3>
          <span class="accordion-icon"><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></span>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-content">
          <p>They are note integrity flags that help identify structural problems in note data.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accordion-item">
        <div class="accordion-header" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false">
          <h3>When should I use Inspector instead of MIDI to CSV?</h3>
          <span class="accordion-icon"><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></span>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-content">
          <p>Use Inspector when you need to debug structure or events. Use CSV when you want note-level analysis in spreadsheets.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

